      <section id="introduction">
        <h2><span>1.</span>Introduction</h2>
        <p>
          In centaur chess – also known as cyborg or advanced chess – humans play in collaboration with an AI that generates a set of moves that the human chooses from. Since the 90s most humans play worse than most mid-level chess AI, but we can still beat the best supercomputers when playing as a human-AI pair.<sup><a href="#note1" class="ref">[1]</a></sup> <mark>What does a future of centaur design look like?</mark> Collaboration with AI is the near future, but what will the profession of graphic design look like in 15 years? <mark>Can we build an ethical future of design?</mark> One that is self critical in its relation to capital and works against inherent injustices of data violence.
        </p>
        <ul class="notes">
          <li id="note1">1. <a href="https://medium.com/conversations-with-tyler/garry-kasparov-tyler-cowen-chess-iq-ai-putin-3bf28baf4dba">"Garry Kasparov on AI, Chess, and the Future of Creativity (Ep. 22)"</a></li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <figure>
        <img src="/thesis-2020/content/img000000084.jpg" alt="">
      </figure>

      <section>
        <p><i>
          This essay is accompanied by images from two styleGAN models: one trained on around 10,000 images of posters by an array of designers from the 70s to today, and one trained on around 3,000 images of logos. These models are freely available on the Runway platform <a href="https://app.runwayml.com/models/oradon/Continue-Graphic-Design-Posters-3-Contemporary">here</a> and <a href="https://app.runwayml.com/models/oradon/Logos-1">here</a> and the output images from the model are <a href="https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1L9yY3WIqdx9CC6i_o9oScW0gVBVIfLDn?usp=sharing">available here</a> for download and free use.
        </i></p>
      </section>

      <figure>
        <img src="/thesis-2020/content/img000000012.jpg" alt="">
      </figure>

      <section id="future">
        <h2><span>2.</span>The Future Is Now</h2>
        <p>
          Many free tools exist today that automate all aspects of design, from generating eSports logos and Instagram stories, to UI and page layouts.<sup><a href="#note2" class="ref">[2]</a></sup> Some researchers estimate that 45% of all activities people are paid to perform can be automated with existing technology.<sup><a href="#note3" class="ref">[3]</a></sup> Automated design tools are currently basically sophisticated templates, but generative adversarial networks (GANs) like pix2pix and styleGAN show that we are approaching some sort of machine learning (ML)<sup><a href="#note4" class="ref">[4]</a></sup> renaissance. The potential is vast: a conversational and frictionless interface that adapts to the user’s way of working,<sup><a href="#note5" class="ref">[5]</a></sup> and new alien strategies. The risks are equally as vast if these tools are built using data systems that reinforce injustices inflicted on vulnerable people,<sup><a href="#note6" class="ref">[6]</a></sup> and if there are no social services offered to people displaced by automation.<sup><a href="#note7" class="ref">[7]</a></sup> Equally important is the effect on the environment that the environmental damage due silicon mining necessary for this automation alone will inflict.<sup><a href="#note8" class="ref">[8]</a></sup> Here is the tangled web of the automation problem: <mark>labor, climate, surveillance, the absence of ethics in big tech and big data, and the possibilities of a post-work future</mark> – it cannot all be solved with graphic design obviously, but design is in a position to intervene.
        </p>
        <ul class="notes">
          <li id="note2">2. Many examples are compiled <a href="https://algorithms.design/">here</a>.</li>
          <li id="note3">3. <a href="https://www.mckinsey.com/business-functions/mckinsey-digital/our-insights/where-machines-could-replace-humans-and-where-they-cant-yet">Mckinsey research</a></li>
          <li id="note4">4. <a href="http://www.r2d3.us/visual-intro-to-machine-learning-part-1/">A visual introduction to machine learning</a></li>
          <li id="note5">5. <a href="https://medium.com/artists-and-machine-intelligence/rethinking-design-tools-in-the-age-of-machine-learning-369f3f07ab6c">Rethinking Design Tools in the Age of Machine Learning</a></li>
          <li id="note6">6. <a href="https://medium.com/s/story/data-violence-and-how-bad-engineering-choices-can-damage-society-39e44150e1d4">Data Violence and How Bad Engineering Choices Can Damage Society</a></li>
          <li id="note7">7. Alex Williams’ and Nick Srinicek’s <i><a href="https://www.versobooks.com/books/2315-inventing-the-future">Inventing the Future</a></i> discusses possible ways this future could look. A recent talk with Williams can be found <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uw0jYF_VFzg">here</a>. Yanis Varoufakis’ recent <a href="https://www.penguin.co.uk/books/111/1117271/another-now/9781847925633.html">book</a> offers another perspective.</li>
          <li id="note8">8. Already the rush to secure deep sea mining contracts <a href="https://thebaffler.com/salvos/deep-sea-rush-mccarthy">has begun</a>. Science fiction has imagined many futures where our rapacious need for new resources moves us to mining asteroids and space colonialism.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          McKenzie Wark’s <i>Capital is Dead</i><sup><a href="#note9" class="ref">[9]</a></sup> posits a new class relation emerging from what others have called platform<sup><a href="#note10" class="ref">[10]</a></sup> or surveillance<sup><a href="#note11" class="ref">[11]</a></sup> capitalism: a hacker class and a vectoralist class. The hacker class spins up new information from nothing and is alienated from the value of their labor, while the vectoralist class controls the vectors through which this information flows.<sup><a href="#note12" class="ref">[12]</a></sup> Designers are positioned strangely within the hacker class because as Michael Rock writes in “Fuck Content,” design operates “in a modulating role between the user and the world.”<sup><a href="#note13" class="ref">[13]</a></sup> <mark>Suppose they gave a war and nobody designed for it?</mark>
        </p>
        <ul class="notes">
          <li id="note9">9. <a href="https://www.versobooks.com/books/3056-capital-is-dead">McKenzie Wark, <i>Capital is Dead</i>, New York: Verso, 2019</a>.</li>
          <li id="note10">10. <a href="https://www.wiley.com/en-us/Platform+Capitalism-p-9781509504862">Nick Srinicek, <i>Platform Capitalism</i>, New York: Wiley, 2016</a>.</li>
          <li id="note11">11. <a href="https://profilebooks.com/the-age-of-surveillance-capitalism.html">Shoshana Zuboff, <i>The Age of Surveillance Capitalism</i>, London: Profile Books, 2019</a>.</li>
          <li id="note12">12. A great conversation around this work can be <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9wBZVEnqocI">found here on Youtube</a>. She has another more design-centric talk <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XgpYjaGFyZU">here</a>.</li>
          <li id="note13">13. <a href="https://2x4.org/ideas/2009/fuck-content/">Michael Rock, “Fuck Content,” <i>Multiple Signatures</i>, New York: Rizzoli, 2013.</a></li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          But of course, our collective power must be more than a refusal to work for unethical corporations or governments, as Erik Carter in “Do You Want Typography or Do You Want The Truth?” addresses, “graphic design has the ability to define our visual landscape, influence culture, and improve products for people but we need to address the issues of politics and prejudice in our profession and start combating them.”<sup><a href="#note14" class="ref">[14]</a></sup> <mark>We should look inward as a profession, and we are!</mark> But what is needed in addition is what David Rudnick discuses in his 2017 Strelka lecture:<sup><a href="#note15" class="ref">[15]</a></sup> new forms of ateliers that support one another<sup><a href="#note16" class="ref">[16]</a></sup> to find what design looks like in the proliferation of new tools and graphic design’s transition into four dimensions and mixed reality interfaces.<sup><a href="#note17" class="ref">[17]</a></sup>
        </p>
        <ul class="notes">
          <li id="note14">14. <a href="https://walkerart.org/magazine/erik-carter-op-ed-do-you-want-typography-or-do-you-want-the-truth">Erik Carter, “Do You Want Typography or Do You Want The Truth?”, <i>The Gradient</i>, 2019</a>.</li>
          <li id="note15">15. <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-ejp4AvetSA">David Rudnick, “Crisis of Graphic Practices: Challenges of the Next Decades,” Strelka, 2017</a>.</li>
          <li id="note16">16. <a href="https://otherinter.net/squad-wealth/">Other Internet’s report “Squad Wealth”</a> discusses current moves towards this new agile atelier model.  The podcast “interdependence” has <a href="https://interdependence.fm/episodes/squad-wealth-and-headless-brands-with-other-internet-LLZU_4Kb">a nice interview with the writers of the report</a>.</li>
          <li id="note17">17. <a href="https://vimeo.com/166807261">Keiichi Matsuda’s “HYPER REALITY”</a> imagines one way this world could look like.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

