      <section id="variable">
        <h2><span>3.</span>Variable Brands</h2>
        <p>
          Variable fonts are typefaces that can be modified using different parameters. The brands of the future will be similarly variable. With minute data about a person’s mood and powerful prediction models, a brand could appear multiple ways to multiple different people. In 2019, Wired founding editor Kevin Kelly predicts that the next platform for big tech companies is a 1-to-1 data replica of the real world,<sup><a href="#note18" class="ref">[18]</a></sup> where each object is indexed and subject to speculative trading. Designs of the future will necessarily be automated because of the near infinite variations of graphics needed to market granularly to each specific consumer.
        </p>
        <ul class="notes">
          <li id="note18">18. <a href="https://www.wired.com/story/mirrorworld-ar-next-big-tech-platform/">Kevin Kelly, “AR Will Spark the Next Big Tech Platform—Call It Mirrorworld,” <i>Wired</i>, 2019</a>.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <figure>
        <img src="/thesis-2020/content/img000000028.jpg" alt="">
      </figure>

      <section id="understand">
        <h2><span>4.</span>Build It</h2>
        <p>
          We all have a hand in the creation of this future because it is our data that’s building it. If we build more open-source tools for automating design, will we have a say in the ethics that accompany this future? <mark>Who is writing the code for our current systems and the systems of the future? What system of ethics are they including?</mark>
        </p>
        <p>
          The easiest way to train a styleGAN model – the machine learning framework used to make the images accompanying this essay – is to use Flickr-Faces-HQ (FFHQ),<sup><a href="#note19" class="ref">[19]</a></sup> a dataset of around 70,000 images of people’s faces pulled from the image-sharing platform flickr. The dataset alone is remarkable: did every one of these people knowingly consent to being included? And what of the thousands of hours of Amazon Mechanical Turk underpaid labor used to pre-process these thousands of images? <mark>There is no ethical creation of automated design tools under capitalism.</mark> We have to evolve our profession in tandem with what will replace it in the years to come.
        </p>
        <ul class="notes">
          <li id="note19">19. In <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/1812.04948 ">“A Style-Based Generator Architecture for Generative Adversarial Networks”</a> from 2018, three researchers at NVidia released the FFHQ dataset available <a href="https://github.com/NVlabs/ffhq-dataset">here</a>.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          The original goal of this project was to build a contemporary poster generator trained on thousands of images of posters by a small set of contemporary graphic designers. The results don’t look like posters at all. The images are swirling and amorphous, sometimes resolving into fabric-like molding grids or Barbara Hepworth-y organic glob patterns. StyleGAN doesn’t work well with sets of images that look wildly different from one another like the set of posters on which it was trained. <mark>To a person with an ML background these outputs are failures, but they are undoubtedly beautiful!</mark> What are the possibilities of further collaboration of this nature where the output is not predetermined by either person or machine but the result of the productive errors of both?
        </p>
      </section>

      <figure>
        <img src="/thesis-2020/content/img000000053.jpg" alt="">
      </figure>

      <section id="access">
        <h2><span>5.</span>Access to Tools</h2>
        <p>
        Many of our digital platforms are built atop stray generosity. Examples abound, from npm packages<sup><a href="#note20" class="ref">[20]</a></sup> to libré fonts,<sup><a href="#note21" class="ref">[21]</a></sup> godot<sup><a href="#note22" class="ref">[22]</a></sup> to stack overflow answers.<sup><a href="#note23" class="ref">[23]</a></sup> The possibilities of free and open source design tools like the 3D program blender<sup><a href="#note24" class="ref">[24]</a></sup> are particularly exciting. Built collaboratively and in conversation, the ethics of these tools are worked out as it is built. What does design have to offer to evolving the interfaces of these community-built tools, making them even more usable and intuitive?
        </p>
        <ul class="notes">
          <li id="note20">20. <a href="https://www.npmjs.com/">npm (node package manager)</a> packages are small bits of open-source code that front-end web developers use to build nearly every project.</li>
          <li id="note21">21. <a href="https://www.are.na/kristian-bjornard/libretype">Many</a> <a href="https://www.are.na/frederic-brodbeck/open-source-typefaces">are.na</a> <a href="https://www.are.na/laurel-schwulst/open-source-web-fonts">channels</a>, <a href="https://usemodify.com/">websites</a>, <a href="https://www.design-research.be/by-womxn/">and</a> <a href="https://velvetyne.fr/">foundries</a> exist cataloging various libré/open-source fonts, <a href="https://oskar.zone/fonts">here are (some of) my personal favorites</a>.</li>
          <li id="note22">22. <a href="https://godotengine.org/">An open-source game engine</a>.</li>
          <li id="note23">23. <a href="https://stackoverflow.com/questions">The lawful good version of Yahoo answers</a>.</li>
          <li id="note24">24. <a href="https://blender.org">blender.org</a>.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
        <mark>When the output of an automated graphic design is indistinguishable from one made by a human, what is the value of the design made by a human?</mark> It is possible that this work will occupy the same space as an artisanal microbrew, valued for the number of unnecessary hours and human touch that went into making it.
        </p>
        <p>
        For educators the task is simple: teach your students to research and adapt. Research strategies will be important as ever as designers transition into managing systems of AI at higher levels. Research can lead to adaptability if students are encouraged to seek out new tools and processes and teach themselves, and adapting to new tools will be necessary as the job of the designer changes.
        </p>
        <p>
        In front-end web development there is a concept of “javascript fatigue:” when one is overwhelmed by the amount of new tools and processes to learn. It is up to all of us to combat this by preserving what excites us in our personal practice, engineering new projects around learning new skills, and bringing in our passions outside the profession to sustain us mentally and challenge us critically. <mark>It’s vital that we also practice skill-sharing and teach each other these emerging tools.</mark>
        </p>
      </section>

