      <section>
        <h2><span>6.</span>The Beautiful Move</h2>
        <p>
          In move 37 of the second game between Google DeepMind’s Go playing program AlphaGo vs. the world champion Lee Sedol, the computer made a move so unexpected that Lee left the tournament room in shock.<sup><a href="#note25" class="ref">[25]</a></sup> The commentators called it “inhuman” and “alien.” Go master Fan Hui, who played and lost against AlphaGo in an earlier tournament, remarked “It’s not a human move. I’ve never seen a human play this move. So beautiful.”
        </p>
        <ul class="notes">
          <li id="note25">25. <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JNrXgpSEEIE">The specific moment is archived here on Youtube</a>. For more on AlphaGo, <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WXuK6gekU1Y">the DeepMind-produced documentary</a> is a good deep-dive.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          <mark>What is a beautiful move in graphic design?</mark> Beauty, like the alien style of play of AlphaGo, is emergent from the various parts (typographic rules, gestalt principles, color theory, strategic rule-breaking, etc.) that make up the whole of a design.
        </p>
        <p>
          AlphaGo used a foundation of the game to make a new style — it played against itself until it learned to beat the best humans in the world. It’s “alien” strategy was an emergent style of play from it’s self-teaching process.<sup><a href="#note26" class="ref">[26]</a></sup> According to Demis Hassabis, CEO of DeepMind, Lee Sedol has begun learning from AlphaGo. So too will designers learn from the new ways of making that AI afford us, and surely in tandem we will build new forms of expression that no human alone could dream.
        </p>
        <ul class="notes">
          <li id="note26">26. <a href="http://johnmenick.com/writing/move-37-alpha-go-deep-mind.html">John Menick, “Move 37: Artificial Intelligence, Randomness, and Creativity,” <i>Mousse</i> 55, 2016.</a>.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

